04515nam a22006375i 9780226540740DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20182018ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2017038282  a9780226540740  a(DE-B1597)522571  a(OCoLC)1028552352  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aTK6653b.G76 2018 4aTK6653b.G76 2018eb 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a621.388/872231 aGross, Benjamin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe TVs of Tomorrow :bHow RCA’s Flat-Screen Dreams Led to the First LCDs /cBenjamin Gross. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b43 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSynthesis00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION: A WORLD OF SCREENS -- t1. THE QUEST FOR MAGNALUX, 1951– 1956 -- t2. A FUMBLING PRELUDE, 1956– 1966 -- t3. SCATTERED ORIGINS, 1961– 1968 -- t4. DISRUPTIVE DISPLAYS, 1968– 1971 -- t5. THE CHANGING OF THE GUARD, 1969– 1976 -- tCONCLUSION: AN INVISIBLE MONUMENT -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1968 a team of scientists and engineers from RCA announced the creation of a new form of electronic display that relied upon an obscure set of materials known as liquid crystals. At a time when televisions utilized bulky cathode ray tubes to produce an image, these researchers demonstrated how liquid crystals could electronically control the passage of light. One day, they predicted, liquid crystal displays would find a home in clocks, calculators—and maybe even a television that could hang on the wall. Half a century later, RCA’s dreams have become a reality, and liquid crystals are the basis of a multibillion-dollar global industry. Yet the company responsible for producing the first LCDs was unable to capitalize upon its invention. In The TVs of Tomorrow, Benjamin Gross explains this contradiction by examining the history of flat-panel display research at RCA from the perspective of the chemists, physicists, electrical engineers, and technicians at the company’s central laboratory in Princeton, New Jersey. Drawing upon laboratory notebooks, internal reports, and interviews with key participants, Gross reconstructs the development of the LCD and situates it alongside other efforts to create a thin, lightweight replacement for the television picture tube. He shows how RCA researchers mobilized their technical expertise to secure support for their projects. He also highlights the challenges associated with the commercialization of liquid crystals at RCA and Optel—the RCA spin-off that ultimately manufactured the first LCD wristwatch. The TVs of Tomorrow is a detailed portrait of American innovation during the Cold War, which confirms that success in the electronics industry hinges upon input from both the laboratory and the boardroom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aTelevisionxReceivers and reception. 0aTelevision-Receivers and reception. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aLCD.  aRCA.  aRadio Corporation of America.  aconsumer electronics.  aflat panel displays.  aindustrial research.  ainnovation.  aliquid crystal displays.  aliquid crystals.  atelevision.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226540740423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226540740/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles